## 3. ☠️ The Flipped Label Trap (Critical)

The core mechanic of this competition — backed by community research:

| Dataset | Flipped Labels |
|---|---|
| Original UCI (303 rows) | **17.41%** |
| Synthetic train (630,000 rows) | **11.09%** |
| Test set | ~11% (assumed same) |

**What happens:**
- Standard models learn the clean clinical logic → CV ≈ 0.953
- Cleanlab removes flipped samples → CV inflates to 0.96+ but **LB collapses**
- Test set still HAS flipped samples → your cleaned model is never right on them
- **The "noise" IS the signal.** Models that adapt to the noise distribution win.

**Correct use of Cleanlab:** Use it to *identify* noisy samples, then **down-weight** them (e.g., `sample_weight=0.3`) instead of dropping. Train on all data.

